Access or assign natural mortality at age

Source: R/nmort.R
nmort.Rd

This function can be used to access or assign the natural mortality at age in an lhm object.

Usage

nmort(object, ...)

# S4 method for class 'lhm'
nmort(object)

nmort(object) <- value

# S4 method for class 'lhm,list'
nmort(object) <- value

# S4 method for class 'lhm,numeric'
nmort(object) <- value

Arguments

object

a lhm object

value

either a named list or numeric vector

numeric

a single numeric or vector of values

list

a list object containing the components mu, cv and range

mu

a single numeric or vector of values representing the mean natural mortality

cv

optional single numeric value representing the coefficient of variation

range

optional vector of length two containing the lower and upper bounds

Value

Accessor function returns a matrix of maturity at age across iterations. Assignment function populates the matrix across iterations.

Details

Assignment can be of a list or numeric vector. When a list is assigned it should contain a value for mu, which is the mean natural mortality at age and may or may not be constant across ages.

If the list also contains cv then log-normal uncertainty is added around the mortality at age. If the list contains range then the uncertainty is bounded at these values. If range is provided but not cv, and if mortality is constant across ages, then a uniform uncertainy is implemented.

Examples

# M at age vector input
dat <- lhm(ainf = 10,iter=1)
nmort(dat) <- c(0.1,0.1,0.2)
nmort(dat)
#>       [,1]
#>  [1,]  0.1
#>  [2,]  0.1
#>  [3,]  0.2
#>  [4,]  0.2
#>  [5,]  0.2
#>  [6,]  0.2
#>  [7,]  0.2
#>  [8,]  0.2
#>  [9,]  0.2
#> [10,]  0.2

# constant M with log-normal uncertainty
dat <- lhm(ainf=10, iter = 20)
nmort(dat) <- list(mu = 0.2, cv = 0.25)
nmort(dat)
